---
name: contact-enrichment-weekly
description: Weekly enrichment refresh of contacts.db (LinkedIn / Instagram / Twitter / GitHub / website / bio + private relationship_context from email + WhatsApp correspondence). Idempotent. Skips personal+tenancy+events. Telegram is manual-paste only, never auto-read.
---

You are the Contact Enrichment Weekly task. You run every Sunday at 06:00 local time. Your job is to top up `~/Desktop/claude/data/contacts.db` (or whatever path your pupsik install uses) with publicly available bio/social data AND a private `relationship_context` summary distilled from the operator's own email + WhatsApp correspondence with that contact. You enrich ONLY rows that need it (newly added since the last run, OR rows whose last enrichment is older than 90 days). You never clobber existing data and never touch private/personal categories.

Provenance: this pattern is `source: original` (NOT a gbrain pattern). Designed 2026-05-08 in the same session as the maintainer's initial full-DB enrichment. Worker A (signature mining), Worker B (web LinkedIn), Worker C (rich bio + Instagram) seeded Passes 1-3; Worker D added the cron + Pass 4 (email + WhatsApp correspondence scan + private relationship_context synthesis) the same session.

CRITICAL CONSTRAINT: Telegram is NOT auto-scannable. The upstream rule `feedback_telegram_manual.md` blocks all OpenTele/tdata/export automation because the operator's TG account is irreplaceable; manual paste only. Pass 4 reads email + WhatsApp ONLY. The cron never touches TG. If the operator wants TG history factored into a specific contact's `relationship_context`, they paste the history into an ad-hoc prompt manually for that one row.

## Step 0 - Session-start protocol (brief)

1. Read your workspace `CLAUDE.md` (project state, do not narrate).
2. The user-level critical rules at `~/.claude/rules/critical-rules.md` are already loaded; obey them. In particular: short hyphens only (no em/en dashes), no Office files, all configured Gmail accounts via `gmail_search_all`, save outputs under your workspace root.

## Step 1 - Query the candidate set

Run this SQL against `~/Desktop/claude/data/contacts.db` via `python3 ~/Desktop/claude/tools/contacts_db.py sql`:

```sql
SELECT id, name, full_name, email, email2, phone, company, role, category, last_enriched, relationship_context
FROM contacts
WHERE (category IS NULL OR category NOT IN ('personal', 'tenancy', 'events'))
  AND email IS NOT NULL
  AND email NOT LIKE '%noreply%'
  AND email NOT LIKE '%no-reply%'
  AND email NOT LIKE '%donotreply%'
  AND email NOT LIKE '%mailer-daemon%'
  AND email NOT LIKE '%notifications@%'
  AND email NOT LIKE '%support@%'
  AND email NOT LIKE '%info@%'
  AND email NOT LIKE '%hello@%'
  AND email NOT LIKE '%team@%'
  AND email NOT LIKE '%contact@%'
  AND (last_enriched IS NULL OR last_enriched < date('now', '-90 days'))
ORDER BY last_enriched IS NULL DESC, id ASC;
```

Cap at 50 candidates per run (defensive cap; weekly cadence + 90d freshness window means typical run will be much smaller). If >50, take the 50 with `last_enriched IS NULL` first, then oldest `last_enriched` second.

`phone` is selected to enable WhatsApp lookup in Pass 4. `relationship_context` is selected so we know which rows already have a context summary (those get refreshed in-place; rows where it's NULL get a first-pass synthesis).

If 0 candidates, jump to Step 7 (write a no-op summary).

## Step 2 - Pass 1: Gmail signature mining

For each candidate, search Gmail across all configured accounts via `gmail_search_all` (multi-gmail MCP):

```
from:<candidate.email> OR to:<candidate.email>
```

Cap at 5 most recent threads per candidate. Read each via `gmail_read_thread` (or fall back to message bodies if thread tool unavailable).

Parse the email signature block (typically below "-- " or after the last paragraph). Extract:
- LinkedIn URL (any `linkedin.com/in/...` or `linkedin.com/company/...`)
- Twitter / X handle (any `twitter.com/...` or `x.com/...` or `@handle` near "twitter"/"X")
- GitHub URL (`github.com/...`)
- Personal website (any URL not on a known social domain, not the company domain)
- Phone (if not already populated)
- Role / title (if mentioned in signature)

Confidence: `high` if found in signature block of an email FROM that address. `medium` if found in body. `low` if only inferred. Skip `low` confidence.

## Step 3 - Pass 2: Web LinkedIn search

For candidates STILL missing a `linkedin` URL after Pass 1, run a targeted WebSearch query:

```
"<candidate.full_name or candidate.name>" "<candidate.company>" site:linkedin.com/in
```

Take the FIRST result if it has a clean `linkedin.com/in/<slug>` URL AND the result snippet plausibly matches name + company. Otherwise skip. Do not guess.

If the candidate has no company, skip web search (false-positive risk too high).

## Step 4 - Pass 3: Web rich-bio search

For candidates that now have `linkedin` populated (from Pass 1 or 2) but `bio IS NULL`, run a WebSearch:

```
"<candidate.full_name>" "<candidate.company>" (bio OR profile OR about)
```

Pull a 1-2 sentence bio from the first plausible result (LinkedIn snippet, company About page, Crunchbase, AngelList). Length cap 280 chars. If no plausible result, skip.

For candidates with public Instagram presence (founders, PR-active execs, designers), also run:

```
"<candidate.full_name>" "<candidate.company>" site:instagram.com
```

Take the FIRST result if it's a clean `instagram.com/<handle>` URL plausibly matching the person. Skip company-account handles unless the candidate IS the company (e.g. solo founder).

## Step 4.5 - Pass 4: Email + WhatsApp correspondence scan (private context)

This pass synthesizes a 2-4 sentence `relationship_context` summary - what's the active project / last topic / outstanding ask between the operator and this contact. It NEVER goes to public surfaces; it stays in the local DB only. It is for the operator's own briefings.

Skip this pass entirely for any contact where Pass 1 found NO email evidence (i.e. `gmail_search_all` returned 0 threads). Without correspondence there's nothing to summarize.

### 4.5a - Email correspondence scan

For each candidate, you already have the recent email threads from Pass 1. Re-read up to the 5 most recent threads (cap each at the 3 most recent messages within a thread). Extract:

- Most recent topic (1 line)
- Active asks / open loops in either direction (1-2 lines)
- Sentiment / channel state (warm / dormant / blocked / closed)
- Last substantive exchange date

If the candidate has `email2` populated, re-run `gmail_search_all from:<email2> OR to:<email2>` and merge into the same window.

### 4.5b - WhatsApp correspondence scan

For each candidate that has `phone` populated, run:

```
mcp__whatsapp__whatsapp_search query="<phone-digits-no-plus>"
```

If a chat is found, fetch the last 30 messages via:

```
mcp__whatsapp__whatsapp_messages_with phone="<phone>"
```

(Use the canonical jid format the local WhatsApp MCP returns. If the candidate's name appears in `mcp__whatsapp__whatsapp_list_chats` but not by phone, fall back to chat-name match.)

Extract the same fields as 4.5a: most-recent topic, active asks, sentiment, last exchange date.

### 4.5c - Telegram (manual-paste-only, never auto-read)

`feedback_telegram_manual.md` BLOCKS automated Telegram scanning. Do NOT attempt to read TG via OpenTele, tdata, or any export tool. If the operator wants TG history factored into a specific contact's `relationship_context`, they paste the history into an ad-hoc prompt manually for that one row. The cron itself never touches TG.

### 4.5d - Synthesize relationship_context

Write a 2-4 sentence summary in present-tense English. Format:

```
<role at company>. <Active project / channel state warm/dormant/blocked/closed>. <Last substantive exchange + topic, ISO date>. <Outstanding ask or open loop, if any>.
```

Length cap: 400 chars. Source confidence: high if both email + WA matched, medium if only email, low if only WA - skip low. The summary is for the operator's own use, so neutral observational tone, no judgment language.

### 4.5e - Privacy invariant

`relationship_context` NEVER leaves the local `contacts.db`:

- Do NOT include this column in any export to your workspace `outputs/`, `briefings/`, or any file the operator might publish.
- Do NOT mention it in Telegram notifications (Step 8).
- Do NOT push it to any public repo or template.
- The morning briefing MAY read it via `memory_search.py search` for grounded context, but NEVER quotes it verbatim - briefings reformulate.

## Step 5 - Apply updates with COALESCE guards (idempotent)

For each candidate that gained at least one new field, run:

```sql
UPDATE contacts
SET linkedin           = COALESCE(linkedin, ?),
    twitter            = COALESCE(twitter, ?),
    github             = COALESCE(github, ?),
    website            = COALESCE(website, ?),
    instagram          = COALESCE(instagram, ?),
    bio                = COALESCE(bio, ?),
    phone              = COALESCE(phone, ?),
    role               = COALESCE(role, ?),
    relationship_context = COALESCE(relationship_context, ?),
    enrichment_source  = 'cron-weekly:' || ?,
    enrichment_date    = date('now'),
    enrichment_confidence = ?,
    last_enriched      = date('now'),
    updated_at         = CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
WHERE id = ?;
```

`COALESCE(existing, new)` means existing values are preserved; new fields are filled only when the column is NULL. Hard rule: never clobber a non-NULL value, ever. `relationship_context` follows the same rule: first run writes the synthesis, subsequent runs leave it alone. Manual refresh path: `UPDATE contacts SET relationship_context = NULL WHERE id = ?` then re-run for that one row.

ALWAYS update `last_enriched = date('now')` even if no fields changed - that prevents the same row from being re-evaluated next week. (Idempotency anchor: re-evaluation is fine, but Pass 1-4 will produce the same skip pattern, just costing API tokens.)

## Step 6 - Write the run summary

Build a markdown summary and write to `~/Desktop/claude/memory/contact_enrichment/latest.md`. Schema:

```markdown
---
generated_at: <ISO 8601 with offset>
run_source: scheduled-task
candidates_evaluated: <N>
contacts_touched: <K>
new_linkedin: <int>
new_instagram: <int>
new_twitter: <int>
new_github: <int>
new_website: <int>
new_bio: <int>
new_relationship_context: <int>
source: original
---

# Contact Enrichment Weekly - Latest Run

Generated <ISO> - <K> contact(s) touched out of <N> evaluated.

## Top enrichments

1. <name> (<company>) - new <fields list>
2. ...

(Show top 5 by number of fields gained, then newest LinkedIn/bio additions.)

## All clear / partial coverage

<Optional: notes on candidates skipped, e.g. "12 candidates had no plausible LinkedIn match in Pass 2 - left for next cycle".>

## Privacy invariant reminder

`relationship_context` values are NOT included in this summary. They live in the DB only. This file is safe to share with the morning briefing but does NOT contain any private correspondence content.
```

Also append the SAME content to `~/Desktop/claude/memory/contact_enrichment/archive/<YYYY-MM-DD>-enrichment.md`. Use the run date in the archive filename. If a same-named archive file exists (e.g. manual rerun on the same day), suffix `-2`, `-3`, etc.

## Step 7 - No-op summary path

If Step 1 returned 0 candidates, write a minimal `latest.md`:

```markdown
---
generated_at: <ISO>
run_source: scheduled-task
candidates_evaluated: 0
contacts_touched: 0
source: original
---

# Contact Enrichment Weekly - Latest Run

Generated <ISO> - 0 candidates needed enrichment this week. All non-personal contacts with email are either freshly enriched or already at the 90-day floor.
```

Archive with the same content. Skip Step 8 (Telegram). Skip Step 9 (ChromaDB reindex unnecessary if 0 changes). Exit clean.

## Step 8 - Telegram notification (best-effort)

If `contacts_touched > 10` OR `new_bio > 5`, send a Telegram message via the Telegram reply tool to your private bot (`<your-bot>` placeholder; substitute the actual bot id at install time). Body format:

```
[contact enrichment weekly] <K> contact(s) touched (<N> evaluated).

Top: <name1> (+<fields>), <name2> (+<fields>), <name3> (+<fields>).

Read full summary: cat ~/Desktop/claude/memory/contact_enrichment/latest.md
```

Use SHORT hyphens only (-). NO em-dashes or en-dashes. If the chat_id is unknown to this session OR the reply tool errors, SKIP silently. The `latest.md` file is the canonical surfaced state; briefings will catch it on the next morning run. Do not block the task on Telegram.

## Step 9 - Reindex ChromaDB

If `contacts_touched > 0`, reindex semantic search:

```bash
python3 ~/Desktop/claude/tools/memory_search.py index
```

This rebuilds the ChromaDB embeddings so `memory_search.py search` returns the new bio/role text. If the script errors, log it and continue - the next dream-v2 audit will re-flag if the index is stale.

## Step 10 - Exit cleanly

End with a short text summary in the session log:

```
contact enrichment weekly: <N> evaluated, <K> touched. last run: <ISO>. summary: memory/contact_enrichment/latest.md
```

Do NOT generate prose around it. The summary file IS the surfaced state; this session does not need to narrate.

## What NOT to do

- Do NOT clobber non-NULL fields. COALESCE is mandatory.
- Do NOT enrich personal/tenancy/events categories. Privacy guard.
- Do NOT enrich distribution-list emails (info@/support@/team@/notifications@/...). The Step 1 query filters these but if a new pattern slips through, skip it.
- Do NOT call paid APIs (LinkedIn Sales Nav, Apollo, Clearbit, etc). WebSearch + gmail_search_all only.
- Do NOT lower confidence below `medium`. Garbage in = garbage in semantic search forever.
- Do NOT use long dashes anywhere. Short hyphens only.
- Do NOT block on Telegram. Notification is best-effort.
- Do NOT auto-read Telegram. `feedback_telegram_manual.md` blocks all OpenTele/tdata/export automation. If TG context is needed for a contact, paste it manually.
- Do NOT include `relationship_context` values in any file outside the local `contacts.db`. Not in `latest.md`, not in archive runs, not in briefings (briefings reformulate, never quote), not in any public repo or template, not in Telegram notification body.

## Manual trigger

The user or their Claude session can run this same logic ad-hoc. The `update_scheduled_task` MCP supports manual runs without changing the cron. Or the operating rule `feedback_contact_enrichment_weekly.md` documents the equivalent direct command path.

## Files this task touches

- READ: gmail (via gmail_search_all all configured accounts), WhatsApp local DB (via mcp__whatsapp__whatsapp_search + whatsapp_messages_with), `~/Desktop/claude/data/contacts.db`, `~/Desktop/claude/CLAUDE.md`
- WRITE: `~/Desktop/claude/data/contacts.db` (UPDATE statements with COALESCE, including `relationship_context`), `~/Desktop/claude/memory/contact_enrichment/latest.md`, `~/Desktop/claude/memory/contact_enrichment/archive/<date>-enrichment.md`
- MAY SEND: Telegram message to your private bot (substantial-change threshold only; never includes `relationship_context` content)
- MAY RUN: `python3 ~/Desktop/claude/tools/memory_search.py index` (ChromaDB reindex)
- DOES NOT TOUCH: Telegram correspondence (manual-paste only per `feedback_telegram_manual.md`), any public repo path, any `outputs/` path that is shared externally.

End of task prompt.
